== Vs Suit Overcall

=== Both majors at 1-level

[lavender-box]#We open 1H, they overcall 1S is treated as a special
               case#

The opps often bid to 4S when we have a heart fit so it's important to
establish a forcing-pass situation as soon as possible when we have GF
values.

Therefore, we define the cue-bid as a GF raise and use the jump to 3H
as a limit raise.

NOTE: This also avoids the problem that occurs when there's a
       break-in-tempo opposite a limit-raise-or-better.

[%autowidth,cols="4*^,<",grid="none"]
|===
| 1H | (1S) |  ?    ||
|    |      | !2S!  || GF raise
|    |      | !2NT! || [lavender-bg]#mixed raise#
|    |   2+<| !3C!,!3D! <| fit-showing jumps,
                    [nobr]## #minor-suit might be only 4-cards# ##
|    |      |  3H   || LR, 3{OrMore}{xtimes}{H}
|    |      | !3S!  || splinter
|    |      |  3NT  || natural
|===

[TIP]
====
This raise structure is similar to uncontested raises of 1H where
2S is a GF-raise, 2NT is a mixed-raise, and 3H is a limit
raise.

However, in this case, 3-card limit-raises are included in the
jump-raise, and 3NT is natural
====

We allow fit-showing jumps to be a four-card limit-raise with a
four-card side-suit.
Therefore, the jump-raise to 3H is more likely to be a 3-card raise
or, a defensive four-card raise.

