[#_fit_showing_jumps]
== Fit-Showing Jumps

A fit-showing jump shows the offence for playing at the level to which it raises

=== Unpassed hand

*We open, they overcall* +
> [lavender-bg]#jump to an unshown minor# = FSJ

*They open, we overcall*,
_ #next hand does not pass# +
> [lavender-bg]#jump to a new suit# = FSJ

****
.Why we only use FSJs to minor-suits after we open

We also play <<#_negative_free_bids,
[alert]#2oM neg.-free bids#>>
by an unpassed hand after we open and they overcall.

When 2oM is an NFB, a jump to 3oM is natural and forcing; not
fit-showing.
****

****
.Why we only use FSJs when next hand bids after we overcall

After we overcall, a new-suit is constructive but not forcing.  So we
need jump shifts to show a good hand (about opening strength) with a
good suit.

When all four-hands are bidding, it is highly unlikely that we have
game on power, so FSJs take priority.
****

==== Restrictions

A jump-shift to game is to play; not fit-showing

FSJs have priority over splinters

If single and double jumps are both available below game in a FSJ
situation, then: +
@ single jump = fit showing +
@ double jump = splinter

****
<<#_js_vs_take_out_double, *We do not play FSJs by an unpassed hand
                            after an opponent's take-out double*>>
****

